# ESP32-C3 Automated Water Top-Off System

Embedded system for automated aquarium/plant water level management. Built on Seeed Xiao ESP32-C3 with PlatformIO/Arduino framework. Features dual float sensor validation, fixed-dose pumping algorithm with EMA rate tracking, web dashboard, IP-based access control, and encrypted credential storage in FRAM.

## Hardware

**Platform:** Seeed Xiao ESP32-C3 (RISC-V, WiFi, 4MB flash)

**Sensors and I/O:**
- 2x float sensors (NC type, pull-up, active LOW) on separate GPIO pins — parallel water level detection
- 1x pump relay output (active LOW) — controls 12V dosing pump
- 1x error signal output — pulsed error codes
- 1x button input (pull-up) — error reset (short press) / provisioning mode (5s hold)

**Peripherals (I2C bus, SDA=GPIO6 SCL=GPIO7):**
- DS3231 RTC — hardware clock with battery backup, NTP-synchronized, UTC storage
- FRAM 32KB (MB85RC256V) — non-volatile storage for credentials (AES-256 encrypted), pump cycle history (ring buffer 60 records), EMA state, algorithm config

**Time management:** RTC stores UTC. Display times auto-converted to local timezone (Poland CET/CEST with automatic DST). NTP sync at boot + hourly via IP addresses (DNS-independent).

## Algorithm

The dosing algorithm is a state machine that delivers a fixed, configurable dose of water each time the float sensors detect a water level drop. A rolling EMA (Exponential Moving Average) tracks the consumption rate (ml/h) and its deviation to generate dynamic alerts.

### State Flow

```
STATE_IDLE
    |  float sensors trigger debounce
    v
STATE_DEBOUNCING  (handled by water_sensors module)
    |  onDebounceComplete callback
    v
STATE_PUMPING     pump runs for exactly: dose_ml / volumePerSecond seconds
    |  pump stops automatically
    v
STATE_LOGGING     save TopOffRecord + EmaBlock + config to FRAM
    |
    v
STATE_IDLE

Any state → STATE_ERROR when:
  - rolling 24h volume >= daily_limit_ml
  - rate deviation >= red alert sigma threshold (after bootstrap)
STATE_ERROR requires explicit reset (web button or GPIO button)
```

### Fixed-Dose Dosing

Each pump cycle delivers exactly `dose_ml` millilitres (default 150 ml, configurable 50–2000 ml). Pump run time is `dose_ml / volumePerSecond`. There is no sensor-release verification — the dose is time-based. This simplifies the algorithm and eliminates false failures caused by slow sensor response.

### EMA Rate Tracking

After each cycle the system calculates:
- **rate** [ml/h] = `dose_ml / interval_since_last_cycle × 3600`
- **ema_rate_ml_h** — EMA of rate (alpha=0.20 default)
- **ema_dev_ml_h** — EMA of absolute deviations `|rate - ema_rate|` — forms the basis of dynamic alert thresholds

Alert thresholds are expressed as sigma multiples:
```
dev_sigma = (rate - ema_rate) / ema_dev × 100

|dev_sigma| >= rate_yellow_sigma (150 = 1.5σ) → yellow warning in GUI
|dev_sigma| >= rate_red_sigma   (250 = 2.5σ) → ERROR state (requires reset)
```

Dynamic thresholds adapt to the actual variability of the environment: a stable aquarium gets tight thresholds, a variable environment gets wider thresholds automatically. Alerts are inactive during the first 5 cycles (bootstrap period).

### Safety Limits

- **Daily volume limit** (`daily_limit_ml`, default 2000 ml) — rolling 24h window; exceeding → ERROR state
- **Available volume tracking** — user enters physical water volume in source container; system decrements after each dose and shows remaining in GUI; inactive if not configured
- **System disable** — manual kill switch via web dashboard; re-enables only by clicking again
- **24h auto-restart** — firmware restarts ESP32 after 24h uptime (pump safely stopped first)

### Cycle Data (TopOffRecord, stored in FRAM ring buffer — 60 records)

Each cycle records: unix timestamp, interval since previous cycle, rate [ml/h], sequential cycle number, deviation in sigma units, alert level, hour of day (circadian analysis), flags (manual trigger, bootstrap, daily limit hit, red alert).

## Tech Stack

| Component | Technology |
|---|---|
| Platform | PlatformIO, Arduino framework |
| MCU | ESP32-C3 (Seeed Xiao) |
| Web server | ESPAsyncWebServer + AsyncTCP |
| JSON | ArduinoJson 7.x |
| RTC | RTClib (Adafruit) — DS3231 |
| Storage | Adafruit FRAM I2C |
| Encryption | mbedtls (AES-256-CBC, SHA-256) — bundled with ESP-IDF |
| Auth | SHA-256 password hash, random session tokens, HttpOnly cookies |

## Security and Access Control

### Network Access Model

```
Incoming request
  |
  +-- Trusted VPS IP (WireGuard tunnel) --> full access, no login required
  |
  +-- IP on whitelist --> rate limit -> session check -> access / 401
  |
  +-- IP NOT on whitelist --> 403 Forbidden (all endpoints, including /login)
```

**IP whitelist** — Hardcoded list of allowed LAN IPs (`config.cpp`). IPs not on the list are permanently blocked from all endpoints.

**Trusted VPS proxy** — A single hardcoded IP (WireGuard tunnel endpoint) bypasses all authentication. Designed for reverse proxy access from a VPS.

**Session authentication** — Login via password (SHA-256 hashed, compared against FRAM-stored hash). Sessions are token-based, bound to client IP, HttpOnly cookie, max 10 sessions total / 3 per IP.

**Rate limiting** — Max 5 requests/second per IP. After 10 failed login attempts, IP blocked for 60 seconds. Whitelisted IPs bypass both mechanisms.

**Credential storage** — WiFi SSID/password, admin password hash, VPS token, device ID stored in FRAM encrypted with AES-256-CBC. Configured via Captive Portal.

### Known Limitations

- HTTP only (no TLS) — traffic visible on WiFi network. Mitigated by IP whitelist.
- Session tokens generated with `random()` — limited entropy on ESP32.
- No CSRF protection on POST endpoints.
- Whitelist is hardcoded — changes require recompilation.

## API Reference

All `/api/*` endpoints require session authentication (cookie). Trusted VPS IP is exempt. Non-whitelisted IPs receive 403 on all endpoints.

### Authentication

| Method | Endpoint | Description |
|---|---|---|
| GET | `/login` | Login page (HTML) |
| POST | `/api/login` | Authenticate (`password` form param) → set session cookie |
| POST | `/api/logout` | Destroy session |

### Dashboard and Status

| Method | Endpoint | Description |
|---|---|---|
| GET | `/` | Dashboard (HTML) |
| GET | `/api/status` | Full system status JSON (sensors, pump, algorithm state, EMA, RTC, WiFi, heap, uptime) |
| GET | `/api/health` | Lightweight health check, no session required. Returns `{status, device_name, uptime}` |

### Pump Control

| Method | Endpoint | Description |
|---|---|---|
| POST | `/api/pump/direct-on` | Turn pump on directly (bypasses algorithm, system-disable, daily limit) |
| POST | `/api/pump/direct-off` | Stop pump immediately (direct mode only) |
| POST | `/api/pump/stop` | Emergency stop (any mode) |

### Configuration

| Method | Endpoint | Description |
|---|---|---|
| GET | `/api/pump-settings` | Get pump config (volume/s, cycle durations) |
| POST | `/api/pump-settings` | Update volume per second (`volume_per_second` param, 0.1–20) |
| GET | `/api/fill-water-max` | Get `dose_ml` and `daily_limit_ml` |
| POST | `/api/set-fill-water-max` | Set daily volume limit (`value` param, 100–10000 ml) |
| POST | `/api/set-dose` | Set single dose volume (`value` param, 50–2000 ml) |
| GET/POST | `/api/system-toggle` | GET: system enabled state. POST: toggle enable/disable |
| POST | `/api/system-reset` | Reset algorithm to IDLE, clears ERROR state |

### Volume Tracking

| Method | Endpoint | Description |
|---|---|---|
| GET | `/api/daily-volume` | Rolling 24h volume, daily limit, dose_ml |
| GET | `/api/available-volume` | Physical reservoir: `{available_ml, available_max_ml}` |
| POST | `/api/set-available-volume` | Set reservoir volume (`value`, 100–20000 ml); sets both current and max |
| POST | `/api/refill-available-volume` | Reset current back to max (quick refill) |

### Statistics and History

| Method | Endpoint | Description |
|---|---|---|
| GET | `/api/get-statistics` | Error counters and last reset time |
| POST | `/api/reset-statistics` | Reset error counters |
| GET | `/api/cycle-history` | Pump cycle history from FRAM ring buffer (newest first) |

## Build and Deploy

Requires [PlatformIO](https://platformio.org/) (CLI or IDE plugin).

```bash
# Build firmware
pio run -e seeed_xiao_esp32c3

# Build and upload
pio run -e seeed_xiao_esp32c3 -t upload

# Serial monitor (115200 baud)
pio device monitor

# Clean build
pio run -e seeed_xiao_esp32c3 -t clean
```

Single build environment (`seeed_xiao_esp32c3`). Partition scheme: `huge_app.csv`.

## Provisioning (First-Time Setup)

Initial configuration (WiFi credentials, admin password, VPS token) is done via Captive Portal.

### Procedure

1. **Enter provisioning mode** — Hold button (GPIO 8) for 5+ seconds during boot. Audio feedback confirms detection.

2. **Connect to AP** — ESP32 starts WiFi access point:
   - SSID: `ESP32-WATER-SETUP`
   - Password: `setup12345`
   - IP: `192.168.4.1`

3. **Configure** — Open browser, captive portal redirects to setup page. Enter device name, WiFi credentials, admin password, VPS auth token.

4. **Reboot** — ESP32 restarts in production mode, loads credentials from FRAM, connects to configured WiFi.

Credentials are AES-256 encrypted before writing to FRAM. To reconfigure, repeat provisioning.

## Troubleshooting

| Symptom | Check |
|---|---|
| FRAM not detected | I2C wiring (SDA=GPIO6, SCL=GPIO7), FRAM power (3.3V), I2C address conflict |
| WiFi not connecting | Re-run provisioning, verify SSID/password in Captive Portal |
| Web inaccessible | Verify your IP is in `ALLOWED_IPS` in `config.cpp`, check ESP32 IP via serial monitor |
| RTC battery warning | Replace CR2032 in DS3231 module |
| Auth fails after FRAM wipe | Re-run provisioning — credentials are stored only in FRAM |
| Pump runs but no water delivered | Check tube connections, verify pump direction, perform calibration |
| ERROR state (pulsing signal) | Daily limit exceeded or red alert (abnormal rate). Reset via "System Reset" button in GUI or short press GPIO button |
| Pump timing wrong (dose too large/small) | Calibrate: run manual pump 60s, measure ml output, set `volumePerSecond = ml/60` in GUI |

## Source Structure

```
src/
  main.cpp                  Entry point, mode detection, main loop
  algorithm/                Fixed-dose state machine, EMA rate tracking, FRAM data structures
  config/                   Settings, pump parameters, system enable/disable
  core/                     Logging utilities
  crypto/                   AES-256 encryption for FRAM credentials
  hardware/                 HAL: FRAM controller, pump, RTC, water sensors (debounce)
  network/                  WiFi manager, VPS cloud logger
  provisioning/             Captive portal: AP, web server, button detection
  security/                 Auth manager, session manager, rate limiter
  web/                      Production web server, API handlers, HTML dashboard
```

## FRAM Memory Layout

```
0x0000–0x0017   Magic number and firmware version
0x0018–0x0417   Encrypted credentials (WiFi, admin password hash, VPS token, device ID)
0x0500+         ESP32 water system data:
  0x0560–0x0573   TopOffConfig (20 bytes, magic 0xA7)
  0x0574–0x0575   Config checksum
  0x0580–0x058F   EmaBlock (16 bytes)
  0x0590–0x0591   EMA checksum
  0x0600–0x0601   Ring buffer record count
  0x0602–0x0603   Ring buffer write pointer
  0x0610–0x0ABF   Ring buffer data (60 × TopOffRecord, 20 bytes each)
```
